{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631276","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631276"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:25:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:25:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17360"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17360"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10050"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70128"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10050"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17360"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55591"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7816"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23540"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70128"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher wants to group similar patients together based on their clinical characteristics. They are deciding between two common clustering methods.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the main difference between hierarchical and k-means clustering?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["K-means clustering only works with numerical data","K-means clustering requires the number of groups to be specified beforehand","Hierarchical clustering can only create two groups","Hierarchical clustering needs labeled training data","Hierarchical clustering only works with categorical data"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECluster analysis is an unsupervised learning technique used to find natural groupings within data. It is particularly useful in medical research for identifying patient subgroups, disease phenotypes, or patterns in genetic data where the groups are not known in advance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key difference is that \u003Cstrong\u003Ek-means clustering requires the number of groups to be specified beforehand\u003C/strong\u003E. In contrast, hierarchical clustering creates a tree-like structure that shows relationships between observations at multiple levels, allowing researchers to decide on the number of groups after seeing the results.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EK-means clustering only works with numerical data\u003C/strong\u003E - While k-means typically works better with numerical data, this is not the main difference between the methods\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHierarchical clustering can only create two groups\u003C/strong\u003E - Hierarchical clustering can create any number of groups\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHierarchical clustering needs labeled training data\u003C/strong\u003E - Both methods don\u0027t require labeled data\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHierarchical clustering only works with categorical data\u003C/strong\u003E - Hierarchical clustering can handle both numerical and categorical data\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth methods are useful tools for finding natural groups in data. The choice between them often depends on whether you know how many groups you want (k-means) or want to explore the grouping structure (hierarchical).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hierarchical cluster analysis groups similar observations together based on their characteristics, creating a tree-like structure called a dendrogram.","K-means clustering requires pre-specification of the number of clusters before analysis begins.","Cluster analysis helps identify natural groupings in data."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55591"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17360"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55591","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55591"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T19:42:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T19:44:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10050"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70128"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,